</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Character Customization - (ELITE CLASSES) </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Distinguishing oneself certainly is something everyone wishes to do. For now, I just wish that one could choose the title they wish and not be stuck with another class's archetype title.
<br />

<br />
I will say that questing for an 'elite' status would be nice and in going with that, I think the trials should be geared to the classes. For an enchanter, there should be trials based on our abilities. So both solo/group encounters that actually test our ability in solo and group roles (and possibly even in between) so that not everyone that meets the minimum requirements can just skip right through and become 'elite'...it needs to be truly earned. So say to even begin attempting for eliteness one must be:
<br />

<br />
- Actually flagged up to and including tier3 (not just in because of min lvl)
<br />
- Max level (so 65 currently)
<br />
- Min amount of AA (you mention 250 but the number isnt so much important)
<br />
- Diff based on flags (ele/time) of chanter/group (would test even the best equiped chanter)
<br />

<br />
however, I do agree that class/race specific skills should remain as such. Even if only a select few can achieve this status, it still takes away some, be it slight, of the uniqueness of those classes/races. (And I chose an enchanter cause JC was suppose to still be of some value at the time and a gnome because I love vertically challenged individuals and they had the unique ability to tinker (now if only it could be made it into something of use)).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Religion! - (whats the point?) </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Religions are a joke, nothing more (save for a few select items such as the Inny necklace they arent of much use). Adding some religion content would be nice, such as diety specific quests that are actually worth doing. however, to suddenly make religions worth having wouldnt be fair to those agnostic folks that selected such since religions didnt offer anything of value at time of creation (should be done via quest...to prove ones self to a diety).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Hirelings! - (what??)</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Think something of this nature would make hard adventures a bit more trivial in most respects. Even if it was only useable by a pet class, regardless of cost...such a pet would ease alot of pressure on groups where dps is a neccessity (such as hard missions). This would basically add a 7th member to the group and that is adding alot with only the money spent being a disadvantge (spending the 5K wouldnt be that much of a bother to those that could regularly use this...specially since it, at this point at least, is no risk...safely add 130dps to a group? count me in).
<br />

