                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Fallere wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In general though, I agree.  Level-restricting mobs goes completely against the spirit of the game.  SoE just has to stop getting their shorts in a bunch every time an unconventional raid/group/individual succeeds at something they weren't expecting.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I disagree.  I like the fact that newbies have mobs to go play with, to go raid.  What I think kills the spirit of the game is those mobs being farmed by people for whom it is no challenge, people who could be doing bigger and better things.  People that should be doing those things and leaving this content for those that cannot.  Without those level caps, Vox and Naggy would be solo'd or single grouped every time they were up.  As they are, they are still something most every low level player looks forward to doing.  That's the spirit of the game.  A raid of 50s fighting a nasty dragon.  Not a 65 farming a dragon for ph@t l3wtz.
<br />

<br />
I'd love to see every item have a required level.  I'd love to see raids capped for people as low as 30.  That way, they can add some content for those levels and the items will be the best they can get...at that level.  Likewise, the older content won't be instantly outdated by the next round of mudflation.  There'd be much more incentive to go get armor for your level if you couldn't buy some recommended level item that drops like candy in a high level zone that has better stats for you than anything you can get yourself...and you don't have to replace it.  And being able to get it themselves would encourage people to spend more time in dungeons, rather than living in outdoor zones.
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately, EQ was never designed with expansion in mind.  And even when you think SOE has learned a lesson, an expansion or two later they show they haven't and do something as stupid as giving all the loot in LDoN recommended levels only.  Works well for my twinks, but it shouldn't have been done that way.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
