<br />

<br />
Don't think so.  
<br />

<br />
People like bigger numbers already.  Bigger is better.  People chase the  carrots.  My gear lets me do what I do now pretty good...I still want better.  Not to mention how many raid mobs are there to non-raid mobs?  You can go solo one that doesn't boot you out to feel tough.  And what if you're a person that doesn't play much?  You'll never get to experience a given level of EQ.  Why should they be denied something special?  There's also a matter of the challenge of the encounters.  Naggy, for example, is pretty simple.  As the level of the raid increases, the encounters get more complex, less forgiving.
<br />

<br />
And, yes, it would mean you couldn't go back and solo certain raid mobs that once took 30 people.  So what?  I'll admit it's fun to see how much tougher you are.  But there's lots of other mobs you can do that on.  Even a nice g-flux on an orc camp does the trick.  Yes, you can't get the loot from those mobs either, but again, so what?  There should be better items available at your level or just ahead of it.  And if it discourages you from levelling for a bit, what's wrong with that?  Long term bad, but for a bit to put aside some xp getting, why not?  Why should level be greater than experiencing the game?
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I've got a feeling EQ is heading toward my way of thinking.  Instanced raids.  Probably have a max level variance (hard to tell now, with the must be 62+ bit).  Minimum number of required people to do the raid.  
<br />

<br />
It's the one thing I want them to add to LDoN...more raids aimed at people below 65, below VT levels, maybe as low as 45-52 range.  That works nicely because a guild that wishes to stick together can always turn on AA xp.  Not because I'll use those raids, but because I would have when I was that level.  Because I believe it gives more for non-hardcore guilds to do, it keeps smaller guilds together, that sort of thing.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
